Loans Dataset¶

by Agustín Ianchina¶

Investigation Overview¶

This presentation contains the highlights of a more extensive exploratory analysis performed on a loan dataset. This explanatory presentations summarizes the following relevant questions:

  • Understand what are the most common loans in terms of: amount, term, status and monthly payment.
  • Is there any kind of relation between the original loan amount and the borrower's income range?
  • Which IncomeRange category pays for the cheaper loans in terms of APR?
  • How many loans do we have in our dataset for each term, and for each IncomeRange Category?
  • What professions have the highest quantity of loans?
  • How does the status of the loan relate to its APR or its amount?
  • How does the status relate to the term and the APR?

Dataset Overview¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Term¶

The following visual shows a distribution of the variable term. It is clear that there are three terms: 36 months(the mode), 60months, and 12months.

Amount¶

A right skewed distribution makes a lot of sense. There are peaks at 5k, 10k, 15k, 20k, 25k. Is this because customers like "round" numbers? Or maybe the bank has special offers/plan/products with this amounts? It does not seem likely that "most of the people has the same needs" regarding the amount of the loan.

Monthly Payment¶

Most of the borrowers pay less than 0.5k, being the mode near 0.27k

mean is 272
mode is [173.71]
87.27% of the borrowers pay less than 0.5k

Status¶

Most of the loans are ongoing or completed. However, there is a % of Chargedoffs and Defaulted. These four categories are the top ones for all the loans.

Original Loan Amount vs Income Range¶

On avearge, higher IncomeRange are correlated with higher LoanAmounts. It makes sense, beacuse we might think that it's safer for the lender. However, it also make us think whether this behaviour might increase inequality in the long term or not.

Income Range vs APR¶

Distributions are very similar for income higher than 0. This stands out vs NotEmployed, category which faces a more left skewed distribution (meanAPR close to 0.28). Higher IncomeRange pays on average lower APR. The minimum goes for +100k with a mean APR close to 0.2. Though all distributions show a "peak"(higher density) in 0.36, this peak is less significant for higher IncomeRanges.

Quantity of Loans vs Income Range and Term¶

The hottest zone is Income Range between 25-75k and 36 months. 25-75k has the highest amount of Loans for all terms. 12 Months Loans has the lowest amount of Loans for all IncomeRanges.

Quantity of Loans vs Income Range and Occupation¶

Other is higher for the 25-75k range. Executive and Professional stand out in +100k.

Loan Status vs Amount (average)¶

Cancelled Loans have the lower Amount (on average). On average, Defaulted, Chargedoff and Completed have quite similar Loan Amounts.(6k)

Loan Status vs Amount (distribution)¶

All cancelled Loans are below 10k.

Loan Status vs APR (average)¶

The lowest three APR Rates are the Completed/Current and Cancelled Loans. The highest APR is for the past due >120d

Loan Status vs APR (distribution)¶

Completed Loans distribution stands out with a high density between 0.1 and 0.15(Same as Final PaymentProgress).

Loan Status vs APR and Term (average)¶

There are no 12 months loans past due>120days. For defaulted loans, 12months loans show on average the highest APR. All cancelled Loans are 36 Months Loans. 12 Month Loans show on average lowest APR for FinalPaymentProgress Loans.
